ScatterPlot With Encircle

df_select <- df[df$age > 800 & 
 df$circumference <= 150 & 
 df$age > 400 & 
 df$age < 1200, ]



gg <- ggplot(df, aes(x=age, y=circumference)) + 
 geom_point(aes(col=circumference, size=Tree)) + 
 geom_smooth(method="loess", se=F) +
  geom_encircle(aes(x=age, y=circumference), data=df_select, color="red", 
 size=2,

df %>% group_by(Tree) %>% summarise(Mean_Circumference = mean(circumference))
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   Tree  Mean_Circumference

df %>% group_by(Tree) %>% summarise(Standard_Deviation_of_Circumference = sd(circumference))

3. Make a linear model which describes circumference (the response) as a function of age (the predictor). Save it as an object with <-, then print the object out by typing its name. What do those coefficients mean?

lr_model1 = lm(circumference~age, df)
print(lr_model1)

7. Does the significant p value prove that trees growing makes them get older? Why not?

print('As the p-value is much less than 0.05 i.e 0.00000000000001931, we reject the null hypothesis that  = 0. Hence there is a significant relationship between the variables in the linear regression model of the data set Orange')
## [1] "As the p-value is much less than 0.05 i.e 0.00000000000001931, we reject the null hypothesis that  = 0. Hence there is a significant relationship between the variables in the linear regression model of the data set Orange"
print('Since Null Hypothesis is rejected and we accept Alternate Hypothesis i.e there is significant relationship between the variables in the linear regression model')
## [1] "Since Null Hypothesis is rejected and we accept Alternate Hypothesis i.e there is significant relationship between the variables in the linear regression model"
print('No significant p-value does not prove that trees growing makes them get older , because it just tells whether they(response and predictors) are dependent or not does not tell about correlation between them for that we use Coefficients if they are positive that means increase in one increases other or vice-versa. Similarly if Coefficients are negative that means increase in one leads to decrease in other or vice-versa.')
## [1] "No significant p-value does not prove that trees growing makes them get older , because it just tells whether they(response and predictors) are dependent or not does not tell about correlation between them for that we use Coefficients if they are positive that means increase in one increases other or vice-versa. Similarly if Coefficients are negative that means increase in one leads to decrease in other or vice-versa."
